06285nam a22007095i 9780774851930DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748519307 a10.59962/97807748519302doi  a(DE-B1597)661742  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aK487.C8.P46 2003eb 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a340.11500aPeople and Place :bHistorical Influences on Legal Culture /ced. by Constance Backhouse, Jonathan Swainger. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b2 b&w illustrations, 5 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPrologue: Louis Knafla and Canadian Legal History -- tIntroduction -- tThe King, the People, the Law … and the Constitution: Justice Robert Thorpe and the Roots of Irish Whig Ideology in Early Upper Canada -- tWilliam Augustus Miles (1796–1851): Crime, Policing, and Moral Entrepreneurship in England and Australia -- tMacleod at Law: A Judicial Biography of James Farquharson Macleod, 1874–94 -- t“Don’t You Bully Me … Justice I Want If There Is Justice to Be Had”: The Rape of Mary Ann Burton, London, Ontario, 1907 -- tMurdered Women and Mythic Villains: The Criminal Case and the Imaginary Criminal in the Canadian West, 1886–1930 -- tBoomtown Brothels in the Kootenays, 1895–1905 -- t“Imagine That! A Lady Going to an Office!”: Janet Kathleen Gilley -- tIncarcerating Holiness: Religious Enthusiasm and the Law in Oregon, 1904 -- tPolice Culture in British Columbia and “Ordinary Duty” in the Peace River Country, 1910–39 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPeople and Place presents a path-breaking collection of essays demonstrating the fascinating ways in which personalities interact with physical locale in shaping the law. Examining law through the framework of history, this anthology presents a mixture of innovative articles produced by established scholars as well as representatives of the next generation. The collection represents a rich array of interdisciplinary expertise, with authors who are law professors, historians, sociologists and criminologists. Their essays include studies into the lives of judges and lawyers, rape victims, prostitutes, religious sect leaders, and common criminals. The geographic scope touches Canada, the United States and Australia. The essays explore how one individual, or small self-identified groups, were able to make a difference in how law was understood, applied, and interpreted. They also probe the degree to which locale and location influenced legal culture history. The essays offer snapshots of human history, capturing the centrality of law as individuals located themselves in relation to others and to the places and times in which they lived. Accessible to academics, students, and general readers interested in the formation of law within a social context, this collection offers a compelling perspective of this subtle relationship. The close examination of people and place will allow readers to unpack law's various meanings across communities and time, and to move closer to a more profound awareness of the complexity of human society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulture and law. 0aLaw and geography. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh1 aBackhouse, Constance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBackhouse, Constance, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrockman, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChunn, Dorothy E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLuca, Kelly, eco